SECTION 12: TRANSFORMER ARCHITECTURE & FUNDAMENTALS\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q39. Explain Transformer architecture with high-level steps.\
\
A: A Transformer processes input in parallel (unlike RNNs which are sequential). High-level\
flow for a standard encoder-decoder Transformer:\
\
1. Input Embedding      \'97 convert tokens to dense vectors\
2. Positional Encoding  \'97 inject position information into embeddings\
3. Encoder Stack        \'97 N layers of (Multi-Head Attention + Feed Forward + LayerNorm)\
                          Builds a rich contextual representation of the input\
4. Decoder Stack        \'97 N layers of (Masked Self-Attention + Cross-Attention + Feed Forward)\
                          Generates output tokens one at a time, attending to encoder output\
5. Linear + Softmax     \'97 project to vocabulary size, pick next token\
\
Example:\
    Translation: "I am happy" \uc0\u8594  "Je suis heureux"\
\
    Encoder reads "I am happy" all at once \uc0\u8594  builds context vectors\
    Decoder generates one token at a time:\
        Step 1: [START] \uc0\u8594  attends to encoder \u8594  predicts "Je"\
        Step 2: [START, Je] \uc0\u8594  attends to encoder \u8594  predicts "suis"\
        Step 3: [START, Je, suis] \uc0\u8594  predicts "heureux"\
        Step 4: predicts [END]\
\
---\
\
Q40. What is Multi-Head Attention and why do we need multiple heads?\
\
A: Attention computes how much each token should "focus on" every other token when building\
its representation. The formula is:\
    Attention(Q, K, V) = softmax(QK\uc0\u7488  / \u8730 d_k) \'b7 V\
\
Multi-head attention runs this in parallel H times with different learned projection matrices.\
Each head learns to attend to different types of relationships simultaneously.\
\
Why multiple heads?\
A single attention head can only capture one type of relationship at a time. Multiple heads\
let the model learn different relationship types in parallel and concatenates the results.\
\
Example:\
    Sentence: "The bank by the river was steep."\
\
    Head 1 might focus on:  syntactic relationships  ("bank" \uc0\u8592  subject of "was")\
    Head 2 might focus on:  semantic context         ("bank" near "river" \uc0\u8594  not financial)\
    Head 3 might focus on:  coreference              (linking pronouns to nouns)\
\
    With only 1 head, the model has to pick one focus. With 8 heads, it captures all of\
    them simultaneously \'97 making the representation much richer.\
\
---\
\
Q41. What is Positional Encoding and why do Transformers need it? How do RNNs manage without it?\
\
A: Transformers process all tokens in parallel \'97 there's no inherent notion of order. Without\
positional encoding, "dog bites man" and "man bites dog" would look identical to the model.\
Positional Encoding adds a position-dependent signal to each token embedding so the model\
knows where each token sits in the sequence.\
\
Original Transformers use sinusoidal functions:\
    PE(pos, 2i)   = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\
    PE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\
Modern LLMs use Rotary Positional Encoding (RoPE) or learned embeddings instead.\
\
How do RNNs manage without it?\
RNNs process tokens sequentially \'97 one at a time, left to right. The hidden state at step t\
is computed from the hidden state at step t-1. Order is baked into the architecture itself \'97\
the model physically cannot see token 5 before token 4. So position is implicit.\
\
Example:\
    RNN processing "I am happy":\
        h1 = f(embed("I"),  h0)\
        h2 = f(embed("am"), h1)   \uc0\u8592  h1 already encodes that "am" comes after "I"\
        h3 = f(embed("happy"), h2)\
    Order is enforced structurally \'97 no explicit encoding needed.\
\
    Transformer processing "I am happy":\
        All three tokens processed simultaneously.\
        Without PE: model sees three vectors with no order \uc0\u8594  "am I happy" = "I am happy"\
        With PE:    each vector gets a unique positional signal added \uc0\u8594  order is preserved.\
\
---\
\
Q42. What is the difference between an Encoder and a Decoder in Transformers?\
\
A: \
Encoder:\
- Reads the full input all at once (bidirectional attention)\
- Every token can attend to every other token\
- Builds a rich contextual representation of the input\
- Used for: understanding tasks (classification, NER, embeddings)\
\
Decoder:\
- Generates output one token at a time (autoregressive)\
- Uses masked self-attention \'97 can only attend to past tokens, not future ones\
  (prevents cheating during training)\
- Also attends to encoder output via cross-attention (in encoder-decoder models)\
- Used for: generation tasks (text generation, translation, summarization)\
\
Example:\
    Encoder-only model:  BERT\
    Task: sentiment classification of "The movie was great"\
    All tokens attend to all others \uc0\u8594  rich bidirectional context \u8594  classify as Positive\
\
    Decoder-only model:  GPT, Claude, LLaMA\
    Task: complete "The sky is"\
    Generates tokens left to right \'97 "blue", then "and", then "clear"\
    Each new token only sees what came before it.\
\
    Encoder-Decoder model: T5, original Transformer (translation)\
    Encoder reads source language \uc0\u8594  Decoder generates target language\
\
