SECTION 14: ML FUNDAMENTALS\
----------------------------------------------------------------\
\
Q46. What is the difference between RNN and LSTM?\
\
A:\
RNN (Recurrent Neural Network):\
- Processes sequences step by step, maintaining a hidden state h_t\
- h_t = tanh(W_h \'b7 h_(t-1) + W_x \'b7 x_t)\
- Problem: vanishing gradient \'97 gradients shrink exponentially as they backpropagate\
  through many steps \uc0\u8594  model forgets long-range dependencies\
\
LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory):\
- Adds a cell state (c_t) \'97 a separate "memory highway" alongside hidden state\
- Uses three gates to control information flow:\
    Forget gate:  how much of past cell state to erase\
    Input gate:   how much of new info to write to cell state\
    Output gate:  what part of cell state to expose as hidden state\
- Gates prevent vanishing gradients \uc0\u8594  LSTMs can remember dependencies 100s of steps back\
\
Example:\
    Task: predict the last word \uc0\u8594  "I grew up in France... I speak fluent ___"\
    \
    RNN:  by the time it reaches "speak", the context "France" from far back has\
          largely vanished from the hidden state \uc0\u8594  likely predicts a generic word\
    \
    LSTM: "France" is written to the cell state at step 5, the forget gate keeps it\
          alive across all intermediate steps, and it's still available at "speak"\
          \uc0\u8594  correctly predicts "French"\
\
---\
\
Q47. Are LLMs bad at classification? If yes, why?\
\
A: LLMs can do classification, but they're often suboptimal compared to fine-tuned\
discriminative models. Here's why:\
\
Reasons LLMs underperform on classification:\
1. They're generative, not discriminative \'97 trained to predict the next token, not to\
   output a probability distribution over fixed labels\
2. Sensitivity to prompt wording \'97 "Is this positive or negative?" vs "Classify sentiment"\
   can yield different results on the same input\
3. Calibration issues \'97 LLM confidence doesn't reliably map to actual probability of\
   being correct\
4. Latency and cost \'97 a fine-tuned BERT does classification in ~50ms for fractions of\
   a cent; GPT-4 takes 1-2s and costs 10-100x more\
5. Label hallucination \'97 LLM might return a label outside the defined set if not\
   constrained\
\
When LLMs ARE useful for classification:\
- Zero-shot or few-shot scenarios with no labeled training data\
- Complex multi-label or nuanced classification where rules are hard to define\
- When the label set changes dynamically\
\
Example:\
    Binary sentiment on 10,000 product reviews:\
    Fine-tuned DistilBERT: 94% accuracy, 40ms/sample, $0.0001/call  \uc0\u8592  better choice\
    GPT-4:                 93% accuracy, 1.5s/sample,  $0.01/call\
\
    BUT \'97 if you need to classify a support ticket into 50 dynamic categories that\
    change monthly, LLM zero-shot wins because retraining a classifier every month\
    is impractical.\
\
